Definition 3.2. Define $\prescript{p}{}{\underline{H}}_{w}=\operatorname{ch}([B_{w}])$ for all $w\in W$ where $\operatorname{ch}:[\mathbf{H}]\overset{\cong}{\longrightarrow}\mathcal{H}$ is the isomorphism of $\mathbb{Z}[v,v^{-1}]$-algebras introduced earlier, and $p$ denotes the characteristic of $k$ as above.
Definition 3.3. The local intersection form of $\underline{w}$ at $x$ is the $k$-bilinear pairing on the graded free $k$-vector space $\operatorname{Hom}_{\nless x,k}^{\bullet}(\underline{w},x)$ given by $\displaystyle I_{\underline{w},x}:\operatorname{Hom}_{\nless x,k}^{\bullet}(% \underline{w},x)$ $\displaystyle\times\operatorname{Hom}_{\nless x,k}^{\bullet}(\underline{w},x)$ $\displaystyle\longrightarrow\operatorname{End}_{\nless x,k}(x)=k\text{,}$ $\displaystyle(f$ $\displaystyle,g)$ $\displaystyle\longmapsto g\circ\overline{f}\text{.}$
Definition 2.2. Let $\mathbf{A}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ be dg-categories. A dg-functor $F$ consists of the following data: • a function $F\colon\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}\to\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{B}$; • for any couple of objects $(A,B)$ of $\mathbf{A}$, a chain map $F=F_{(A,B)}\colon\mathbf{A}(A,B)\to\mathbf{B}(F(A),F(B)),$ subject to the usual associativity and unitality axioms.
Definition 4.4. Let $F,G\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ be $A_{\infty}$-functors. A degree $g$ pre-natural transformation $h\colon F\to G$ is consists of a sequence of maps $(h^{0},h^{1},\ldots)$ such that $h^{0}\colon X\mapsto h^{0}_{X}\in\mathbf{B}(F(X),G(X))^{g},\quad X\in\mathbf{A},$ and $h^{d}$ is a family of multilinear maps $h^{d}\colon\mathbf{A}(X_{d-1},X_{d})\otimes\ldots\otimes\mathbf{A}(X_{0},X_{1}% )\to\mathbf{B}(F(X_{0}),G(X_{d}))[g-d]$ for any family of objects $X_{0},\ldots,X_{d}\in\mathbf{A}$. Pre-natural transformations $F\to G$ form the graded vector space $\operatorname{Fun_{\infty}}(\mathbf{A},\mathbf{B})(F,G)$. Compositions are described in [Sei08, Paragraph (1d)]. For example, we have that $\mu^{1}(h)^{0}_{X}=\mu^{1}_{\mathbf{B}}(h^{0}_{X}),\quad\forall\,X\in\mathbf{A}.$ Moreover, we require the strict unitality condition: $h^{d}(f_{d-1},\ldots,f_{n+1},1_{X_{n}},f_{n},\ldots,f_{1})=0,$ for all $d\geq 1$ and $0\leq n<d$, with $f_{k}\in\mathbf{A}(X_{k-1},X_{k})$.
Definition 4.1. A strictly unital $A_{\infty}$-category $\mathbf{A}$ consists of a set of objects $\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$, a graded $\mathbf{k}$-vector space $\mathbf{A}(X_{0},X_{1})$ for any couple of objects $X_{0},X_{1}\in\mathbf{A}$, and multilinear composition maps for any order $d\geq 1$: $\mu^{d}_{\mathbf{A}}\colon\mathbf{A}(X_{d-1},X_{d})\otimes\ldots\otimes\mathbf% {A}(X_{0},X_{1})\to\mathbf{A}(X_{0},X_{d})[2-d],$ satisfying the following collection of equations (for all $d\geq 1$): $\sum_{m=1}^{d}\sum_{n=0}^{d-m}(-1)^{\maltese_{n}}\mu_{\mathbf{A}}^{d-m+1}(f_{d% },\ldots,f_{n+m+1},\mu^{m}_{\mathbf{A}}(f_{n+m},\ldots,f_{n+1}),f_{n},\ldots,f% _{1})=0,$ where by definition $\maltese_{n}=|f_{1}|+\ldots+|f_{n}|-n$. Moreover, for any object $X\in\mathbf{A}$, there exists a (necessarily unique) morphism $1_{X}\in\mathbf{A}(X,X)^{0}$ which satisfies: $\begin{split}&\displaystyle\mu^{1}_{\mathbf{A}}(1_{X})=0,\\ &\displaystyle(-1)^{|f|}\mu^{2}_{\mathbf{A}}(1_{X_{1}},f)=\mu^{2}_{\mathbf{A}}% (f,1_{X_{0}})=f,\quad\forall\,f\in\mathbf{A}(X_{0},X_{1}),\\ &\displaystyle\mu^{d}_{\mathbf{A}}(f_{d-1},\ldots,f_{n+1},1_{X_{n}},f_{n},% \ldots,f_{1})=0,\\ &\displaystyle\forall\,d>2,f_{k}\in\mathbf{A}(X_{k-1},X_{k}),\forall\,0\leq n<% d.\end{split}$
Definition 5.2. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category, and let $\mathbf{B}$ be a full dg-subcategory of $\mathbf{A}$. A dg-quotient of $\mathbf{A}$ modulo $\mathbf{B}$ is a dg-category $\mathbf{A}/\mathbf{B}$ together with a quasi-functor $\pi\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{A}/\mathbf{B}$, such that for any dg-category $\mathbf{C}$ the induced functor $\pi^{*}\colon H^{0}(\operatorname{\mathbb{R}\underline{Hom}}(\mathbf{A}/% \mathbf{B},\mathbf{C}))\to H^{0}(\operatorname{\mathbb{R}\underline{Hom}}(% \mathbf{A},\mathbf{C}))$ is fully faithful, and its essential image consists of quasi-functors $F\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{C}$ such that $H^{0}(F)$ maps objects of $\mathbf{B}$ to zero objects in $H^{0}(\mathbf{C})$.
Definition 2.6. A dg-category $\mathbf{A}$ is pretriangulated if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})\hookrightarrow\mathrm{tria}(\mathbf{A})$ is an equivalence; it is triangulated if $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})\hookrightarrow\mathrm{per}(\mathbf{A})$ is an equivalence.
Definition 4.6. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category (here, not viewed as an $A_{\infty}$-category). The dg-category of (homotopy coherent) morphisms $\operatorname{\underline{Mor}}\mathbf{A}$ \nomenclature$\operatorname{\underline{Mor}}\mathbf{A}$The dg-category of homotopy coherent morphisms in a dg-category $\mathbf{A}$ is defined as follows. Objects are triples $(A,B,f)$, where $f\in Z^{0}(\mathbf{A}(A,B))$. A degree $n$ morphism $(A,B,f)\to(A^{\prime},B^{\prime},f^{\prime})$ is given by a lower triangular matrix $(u,v,h)=\begin{pmatrix}u&0\\ h&v\end{pmatrix},$ where $u\in\mathbf{A}(A,A^{\prime})^{n}$, $v\in\mathbf{A}(B,B^{\prime})^{n}$ and $h\in\mathbf{A}(A,B)^{n-1}$. Compositions are defined by matrix multiplication with a sign rule: $\begin{pmatrix}u^{\prime}&0\\ h^{\prime}&v^{\prime}\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}u&0\\ h&v\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}u^{\prime}u&0\\ (-1)^{n}h^{\prime}u+v^{\prime}h&v^{\prime}v\end{pmatrix},$ whenever $(u,v,h)$ has degree $n$. The differential of a morphism $(u,v,h)\colon(A,B,f)\to(A^{\prime},B^{\prime},f^{\prime})$ of degree $n$ is defined by $d\begin{pmatrix}u&0\\ h&v\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}du&0\\ dh+(-1)^{n}(f^{\prime}u-vf)&dv\end{pmatrix}.$
Definition 2.5. Let $\mathbf{A}$ be a dg-category. The underlying category (resp. the homotopy category) of $\mathbf{A}$ is the category $Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})$ (resp. $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})$) which is defined as follows: • $\operatorname{Ob}Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})=\operatorname{Ob}H^{0}(\mathbf{A})=% \operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$, • $Z^{0}(\mathbf{A})(A,B)=Z^{0}(\mathbf{A}(A,B))$ (respectively $H^{0}(\mathbf{A})(A,B)=H^{0}(\mathbf{A}(A,B))$), for all $A,B\in\mathbf{A}$, with natural compositions and identities.
Definition 4.2. Let $\mathbf{A}$ and $\mathbf{B}$ be (strictly unital) $A_{\infty}$-categories. An $A_{\infty}$-functor $F\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ consists of a map of sets $\displaystyle F^{0}\colon\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$ $\displaystyle\to\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{B},$ $\displaystyle X$ $\displaystyle\mapsto F^{0}(X)=F(X),$ and multilinear maps $F^{d}\colon\mathbf{A}(X_{d-1},X_{d})\otimes\ldots\otimes\mathbf{A}(X_{0},X_{1}% )\to\mathbf{B}(F(X_{0}),F(X_{d}))[1-d],$ subject to the following equations, for all $d\geq 1$: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\sum_{r\geq 1}&\displaystyle\sum_{s_{1}+\ldots+s_{r}% =d}\mu^{r}_{\mathbf{B}}(F^{s_{r}}(f_{d},\ldots,f_{d-s_{r}+1}),\ldots,F^{s_{1}}% (f_{s_{1}},\ldots,f_{1}))\\ &\displaystyle=\sum_{m=1}^{d}\sum_{n=0}^{d-m}(-1)^{\maltese_{n}}F^{d-m+1}(f_{d% },\ldots,f_{n+m+1},\mu^{m}_{\mathbf{A}}(f_{n+m},\ldots,f_{n+1}),f_{n},\ldots,f% _{1}),\end{split}$ where $s_{i}\geq 1$ for all $i$. Moreover, $F$ is required to satisfy the following strict unitality condition: $\begin{split}&\displaystyle F^{1}(1_{X})=1_{F(X)},\quad\forall\,X\in\mathbf{A}% ,\\ &\displaystyle F^{d}(f_{d-1},\ldots,f_{n+1},1_{X_{n}},f_{n},\ldots,f_{1})=0,\\ &\displaystyle\forall\,d\geq 2,f_{k}\in\mathbf{A}(X_{k-1},X_{k}),\forall\,0% \leq n<d.\end{split}$ Given $A_{\infty}$-functors $F\colon\mathbf{A}\to\mathbf{B}$ and $G\colon\mathbf{B}\to\mathbf{C}$, their composition $G\circ F$ is defined as follows: $\begin{split}\displaystyle(G\circ F)^{0}&\displaystyle=G^{0}\circ F^{0},\\ \displaystyle(G\circ F)^{d}&\displaystyle(f_{d},\ldots,f_{1})\\ &\displaystyle=\sum_{r\geq 1}\sum_{s_{1}+\ldots+s_{r}=d}G^{r}(F^{s_{r}}(f_{d},% \ldots,f_{d-s_{r}+1}),\ldots,F^{s_{1}}(f_{s_{1}},\ldots,f_{1})),\end{split}$ whenever $d\geq 1$, with $s_{i}\geq 1$.
Definition 2.1. A differential graded (dg-) category $\mathbf{A}$ consists of a set of objects $\operatorname{Ob}\mathbf{A}$, a hom-complex $\mathbf{A}(A,B)$ for any couple of objects $A,B$, and (unital, associative) composition chain maps of complexes of $\mathbf{k}$-modules: $\begin{split}\displaystyle\mathbf{A}(B,C)\otimes\mathbf{A}(A,B)&\displaystyle% \to\mathbf{A}(A,C),\\ \displaystyle g\otimes f&\displaystyle\mapsto gf=g\circ f\end{split}$
Definition 1.1 (Pre-crossed modules and crossed modules) A pre-crossed module $(E,R,\partial)$, of (commutative) algebras, is given by an algebra map $\partial\colon E\to R$, with $E$ and $R$ commutative, together with an action $\blacktriangleright$ of $R$ on $E$, such that the following relation, called the “first Peiffer-Whitehead relation”, holds: XM1) $\partial(r\blacktriangleright e)=r\,\partial(e)$, for each $e\in E$ and $r\in R$. A crossed module of algebras $(E,R,\partial)$ is a pre-crossed module satisfying, furthermore, the “second Peiffer-Whitehead relation”: XM2) $\partial(e)\blacktriangleright e^{\prime}=e\,e^{\prime}$, for all $e,e^{\prime}\in E$.
Definition 1.3 Let $(E,R,\partial)$ and $(E^{\prime},R^{\prime},\partial^{\prime})$ be two crossed modules. A crossed module morphism $f\colon(E,R,\partial)\to(E^{\prime},R^{\prime},\partial^{\prime})$ is a pair $f=(f_{1}\colon E\to E^{\prime},f_{0}\colon R\to R^{\prime})$ of algebra maps, preserving the action of $R$ on $E$, in the sense that $f_{1}(r\blacktriangleright e)=f_{0}(r)\blacktriangleright f_{1}(e),\forall e% \in E,\forall r\in R$, furthermore making the diagram below commutative:
Definition 1.2. A space $A$ is detectable if there is a theory $T$ with the property that a space $X$ is weakly equivalent to the underlying space of a $T$-algebra if and only if $X$ is weakly equivalent to $\mathbf{Map_{*}}(A,Y)$ for some $Y$.
Definition 3.5. Let $C$ be a closed class. A pointed simplicial set $A$ is called homotopy projective relative to $C$ if $\mathbf{Map_{*}}(A,-)$ commutes with homotopy colimits of filtered or simplicial diagrams which take their value in $C$. A space $A$ is called homotopy self-projective if it is homotopy projective relative to Cell $A$.
Definition 2.3. The map $\epsilon_{*}:|FU_{\bullet}X|\rightarrow X$ is called Bar Resolution of $X$.
Definition 3.3. A nonempty class of simplicial sets is said to be closed if it is closed under homotopy colimits and weak equivalences. The smallest closed class which contains a simplicial set $A$ is called the class of $A$-cellular spaces, denoted Cell $A$.
Definition 1.1. A theory $T$ is a based simplicial category with objects $t_{0},t_{1},t_{2},...$ such that $t_{i}$ is the $i$-fold product of $t_{1}$. In particular, $t_{0}$ is the basepoint. An algebra over $T$ is a based, product preserving functor $X$ from $T$ into based simplicial sets. The underlying space of $X$ is $X(t_{1})$.
Definition 2.1. Let $A$ be a space. The theory $T_{A}$ just described is called the Canonical Theory Associated to $A$.
Definition 1.5. (See [AGM, Definition 2.7], [AHT, Definition 2.1] and [MS, Definitions 2.10 and 2.14]) Fix a $N\in\mathbb{N}$. A functor $R$ is said to have a monadic decomposition of monadic length $N$ when there exists a sequence $\left(R_{n}\right)_{n\leq N}$ of functors $R_{n}$ such that 1) $R_{0}=R$; 2) for $0\leq n\leq N$, the functor $R_{n}$ has a left adjoint functor $L_{n}$; 3) for $0\leq n\leq N-1$, the functor $R_{n+1}$ is the comparison functor induced by the adjunction $\left(L_{n},R_{n}\right)$ with respect to its associated monad; 4) $L_{N}$ is full and faithful while $L_{n}$ is not full and faithful for $0\leq n\leq N-1.$ A functor $R$ having monadic length $N$ is equivalent to requiring that the forgetful functor $U_{N,N+1}$ defines an isomorphism of categories and that no $U_{n,n+1}$ has this property for $\leq n\leq N-1$ (see [AGM, Remark 2.4]). Note that for a functor $R:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}$ having a monadic decomposition of monadic length $N$, we thus have a diagram $\xymatrixcolsep{2cm}\xymatrix{\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{0}}&\mathcal{A}\ar@% <.5ex>[d]^{R_{1}}\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}&\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{% R_{2}}\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A}}}&\cdots\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A% }}}\quad\cdots&\mathcal{A}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R_{N}}\ar[l]_{\mathrm{Id}_{\mathcal{A% }}}\\ \mathcal{B}_{0}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{0}}&\mathcal{B}_{1}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L% _{1}}\ar[l]_{U_{0,1}}&\mathcal{B}_{2}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{2}}\ar[l]_{U_{1,2}% }&\cdots\ar[l]_{U_{2,3}}\quad\cdots&\mathcal{B}_{N}\ar@<.5ex>@{.>}[u]^{L_{N}}% \ar[l]_{U_{N-1,N}}}$ where $\mathcal{B}_{0}=\mathcal{B}$ and, for $1\leq n\leq N,$ • $\mathcal{B}_{n}$ is the category of $\left(R_{n-1}L_{n-1}\right)$-algebras ${{}_{R_{n-1}L_{n-1}}\mathcal{B}}_{n-1}$; • $U_{n-1,n}:\mathcal{B}_{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{n-1}$ is the forgetful functor ${{}_{R_{n-1}L_{n-1}}}U$. We will denote by $\eta_{n}:{{\mathsf{i}d}}_{\mathcal{B}_{n}}\rightarrow R_{n}L_{n}$ and $\epsilon_{n}:L_{n}R_{n}\rightarrow{{\mathsf{i}d}}_{\mathcal{A}}$ the unit, resp. counit of the adjunction $\left(L_{n},R_{n}\right)$ for $0\leq n\leq N$. Note that one can introduce the forgetful functor $U_{m,n}:\mathcal{B}_{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{m}$ for all $m\leq n$ with $0\leq m,n\leq N$.
Definition 2.5. Following [BMW, 1.4], an adjoint square as in (3) is called exact whenever both $\zeta{}_{11}:L^{\prime}G\rightarrow FL$ and $\zeta_{22}:GR\rightarrow R^{\prime}F$ are isomorphisms. Note that this implies that the given diagram commutes -up to isomorphism- when either the left adjoint functors or the right adjoint functors are omitted.
Definition 1.3. An adjunction $(L:\mathcal{B}\rightarrow\mathcal{A},R:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow\mathcal{B})$ is called monadic (tripleable in Beck’s terminology [Bec, Definition 3]) whenever the comparison functor $K:\mathcal{A}\rightarrow{{}_{RL}}\mathcal{B}$ is an equivalence of categories. A functor $R$ is called monadic if it has a left adjoint $L$ such that the adjunction $(L,R)$ is monadic, see [Bec, Definition 3’].
Definition 1.8. We say that a functor $R$ is comparable whenever there exists a sequence $\left(R_{n}\right)_{n\in\mathbb{N}}$ of functors $R_{n}$ such that $R_{0}=R$ and, for $n\in\mathbb{N}$, 1) the functor $R_{n}$ has a left adjoint functor $L_{n}$; 2) the functor $R_{n+1}$ is the comparison functor induced by the adjunction $\left(L_{n},R_{n}\right)$ with respect to its associated monad. In this case we have a diagram as (1) but not necessarily stationary. Hence we can consider the forgetful functors $U_{m,n}:\mathcal{B}_{n}\rightarrow\mathcal{B}_{m}$ for all $m\leq n$ with $m,n\in\mathbb{N}$.
Definition 3.1. (due to Jacobson, see [Jac, page 210]) A restricted Lie algebra over $\Bbbk$ (also called $p$-Lie algebra by some authors) is a triple $(L,[-,-],{-}^{[p]})$ consisting of a (ordinary) Lie algebra $(L,[-,-])$ (i.e. a $\Bbbk$-vector space $L$ endowed with a $\Bbbk$-bilinear map $[-,-]$ satisfying the antisymmetry and Jacobi condition) and a (set-theoretical) map ${-}^{[p]}:L\to L$ satisfying $\displaystyle(\alpha x)^{[p]}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle{\alpha^{p}x^{[p]}}\textrm{~{}for~{}all~{}}x\in L,\alpha\in\Bbbk;$ $\displaystyle\mathrm{ad}(x^{[p]})$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle(\mathrm{ad}(x))^{p}\textrm{~{}for~{}all~{}}x\in L;$ $\displaystyle(x+y)^{[p]}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle x^{[p]}+y^{[p]}+s(x,y)\textrm{~{}for~{}all~{}}x,y\in L,$ where $\mathrm{ad}$ is the adjoint representation of $L$; $\mathrm{ad}:L\to\mathrm{End}(L),x\mapsto{\mathrm{ad}}_{x}~{}~{}\mathrm{where}~% {}{\mathrm{ad}}_{x}(y)=[x,y],$ and $s(x,y)=\sum_{i=1}^{p-1}\frac{s_{i}(x,y)}{i}$, where $s_{i}(x,y)$ is the coefficient of ${\beta}^{i-1}$ in the expansion of $({\mathrm{ad}}(\beta x+y))^{p-1}(x)$. A map $f:(L,[-,-],{-}^{[p]})\to(L^{\prime},[-,-]^{\prime},{-}^{[p^{\prime}]})$ is a morphism of restricted Lie algebras if $f$ is a morphism of (ordinary) Lie algebras $f:(L,[-,-])\to(L^{\prime},[-,-]^{\prime})$ such that $f(x^{[p]})=(f(x))^{[p^{\prime}]},$ for all $x\in L$. The category of restricted Lie algebras with their morphisms will be denoted by ${\mathsf{Lie}_{p}}$.
Definition 2.1. Recall from [Gra, Definition I,6.7] that an adjoint square consists of a (not necessarily commutative) diagram of functors as depicted below ($(L,R)$ and $(L^{\prime},R^{\prime})$ being adjunctions with units $\eta$ resp. $\eta^{\prime}$ and counits $\epsilon$ resp. $\epsilon^{\prime}$) together with a matrix of natural transformations “inside”: $\begin{array}[]{ccc}\xymatrixrowsep{25pt}\xymatrixcolsep{3cm}\xymatrix{\ar@{}[% dr]|{\left(\begin{array}[]{cc}\zeta_{11}&\zeta_{12}\\ \zeta_{21}&\zeta_{22}\end{array}\right)}\mathcal{A}\ar[r]^{F}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R}% \hfil&\mathcal{A}^{\prime}\ar@<.5ex>[d]^{R^{\prime}}\\ \mathcal{B}\ar@<.5ex>[u]^{L}\ar[r]_{G}&\mathcal{B}^{\prime}\ar@<.5ex>[u]^{L^{% \prime}}&&\end{array}\qquad\begin{array}[]{cc}\zeta_{11}:L^{\prime}G% \rightarrow FL,&\zeta_{12}:L^{\prime}GR\rightarrow F,\\ \zeta_{21}:G\rightarrow R^{\prime}FL,&\zeta_{22}:GR\rightarrow R^{\prime}F,% \end{array}}$ These ingredients are required to be subject to the following equalities: $\displaystyle\zeta_{11}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle\zeta_{12}L\circ L^{\prime}G\eta=\epsilon^{\prime}FL\circ L^{% \prime}\zeta_{21}=\epsilon^{\prime}FL\circ L^{\prime}\zeta_{22}L\circ L^{% \prime}G\eta,$ $\displaystyle\zeta_{12}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle F\epsilon\circ\zeta_{11}R=\epsilon^{\prime}F\epsilon\circ L^{% \prime}\zeta_{21}R=\epsilon^{\prime}F\circ L^{\prime}\zeta_{22},$ $\displaystyle\zeta_{21}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle R^{\prime}\zeta_{11}\circ\eta^{\prime}G=R^{\prime}\zeta{}_{12}L% \circ\eta^{\prime}G\eta=\zeta_{22}L\circ G\eta,$ $\displaystyle\zeta_{22}$ $\displaystyle=$ $\displaystyle R^{\prime}F\epsilon\circ R^{\prime}\zeta_{11}R\circ\eta^{\prime}% GR=R^{\prime}\zeta_{12}\circ\eta^{\prime}GR=R^{\prime}F\epsilon\circ\zeta_{21}R.$ We call such natural transformations transposes of each other. If only one of the entries of the matrix is given, its transposes can be defined by means of the equalities above.
Definition 1.4. ([AT, page 231]) A monad $\left(Q,m,u\right)$ is called idempotent if $m$ is an isomorphism. An adjunction $\left(L,R\right)$ is called idempotent whenever the associated monad is idempotent.
Definition 16. A linear representation of a convex monoid $X$ consists of a vector space $V$ and a monoid homomorphism $\rho:X\to\operatorname{Aut}(V)$ that preserves convex combinations.
Definition 2. A compact quantum group is a $\mathrm{C}^{*}$-algebra $A$ equipped with a *-homomorphism $\Delta:A\to A\otimes A$ called the comultiplication, such that • The comultiplication is coassociative, i.e. $(\Delta\otimes\mathrm{id}_{A})\circ\Delta=(\mathrm{id}_{A}\otimes\Delta)\circ\Delta$. • The linear spans of $\Delta(A)(1\otimes A)$ and $\Delta(A)(A\otimes 1)$ are dense in $A\otimes A$.
Definition 9. A convex monoid is an object $X$ of the category $\mathbf{KConv}$, together with a continuous multiplication map $\cdot:X\times X\to X$ and a constant $1\in X$, such that • The operation $\cdot$ is affine in both variables separately, that is, $(\lambda x+(1-\lambda)y)\cdot z=\lambda x\cdot z+(1-\lambda)y\cdot z$ and similarly for convex combinations on the right. • The operation $\cdot$ is associative. • $1$ is a unit for $\cdot$.
Definition 4. An effect module consists of a set $A$ equipped with a partial binary operation $\boxplus$ called addition, a unary operation $(-)^{\bot}$ called orthocomplement, a scalar multiplication $\cdot:[0,1]\times A\to A$ and constants $0,1\in A$, subject to the following axioms: • The operation $\boxplus$ is commutative, which means that whenever $a\boxplus b$ is defined, then also $b\boxplus a$ is defined, and $a\boxplus b=b\boxplus a$. • The operation $\boxplus$ is associative, which means that if $a\boxplus b$ and $(a\boxplus b)\boxplus c$ are defined, then also $b\boxplus c$ and $a\boxplus(b\boxplus c)$ are defined, and $(a\boxplus b)\boxplus c=a\boxplus(b\boxplus c)$. • For every $a\in A$, $a\boxplus 0=0\boxplus a=a$. • For all $a,b\in A$, $a\boxplus b=1$ if and only if $b=a^{\bot}$. • If $a\boxplus 1$ is defined, then $a=0$. • For all $r,s\in[0,1]$ and $a\in A$, $r\cdot(s\cdot a)=(rs)\cdot a$. • If $r+s\leq 1$, then $(r+s)\cdot a=r\cdot a+s\cdot a$. • If $a\boxplus b$ is defined, then $r\cdot(a\boxplus b)=r\cdot a\boxplus r\cdot b$. • $1\cdot a=a$. Effect modules form a category $\mathbf{EMod}$, in which the morphisms are functions preserving addition, orthocomplement, scalar multiplication, and the constants $0$ and $1$.
Definition 11. A Hilbert algebra is a *-algebra $A$ equipped with an inner product $\langle-\mid-\rangle$, such that (1) For all $a,b\in A$, $\langle a\mid b\rangle=\langle b^{*}\mid a^{*}\rangle$. (2) For each $a\in A$, the map $b\mapsto ab$ is a bounded operator. (3) For all $a,b,c\in A$, $\langle ab\mid c\rangle=\langle b\mid a^{*}c\rangle$. (4) The linear span of $\{ab\mid a,b\in A\}$ is dense in $A$.
Definition 5.1. ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a Haagerup-Izumi fusion category if: $K_{0}({\mathcal{C}})=\mathbb{Z}[G\cup\{g\rho\,|\,g\in G\}]$ with multiplication given by the group law and: $g(h\rho)=(gh)\rho=(h\rho)g^{-1}$ $(g\rho)(h\rho)=gh^{-1}+\sum\limits_{a\in G}g\rho$
Definition 2.1. Let $G$ be a finite abelian group. A fusion category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is a near group if its Grothendieck ring is given by: $K_{0}({\mathcal{C}})=\mathbb{Z}[G\cup\{\rho\}]$ with multiplication given by the group law and: $\rho g=\rho=g\rho\quad\textrm{and}\quad\rho^{2}=\sum\limits_{g\in G}g+m\rho$ As shown by [EvGan12, Theorem 2(a)], near group fusion categories are divided into two types: I: $m=|G|-1$, or II: $m=k|G|$ for some $k\in\mathbb{N}$
Definition 4.1. Let $(G,q)$ be a pre-metric group. Then the associated Gauss sum is given by: $\Theta(G,q)=\frac{1}{\sqrt{|G|}}\sum\limits_{g\in G}e^{2\pi iq(g)}$
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a pivotal fusion category. Then, for $V\in{\mathcal{C}}$ we define the $k^{\text{th}}$ Frobenius-Schur indicator by the following trace: $\nu_{k}(V)=\operatorname{Tr}\left(E^{(k)}_{V}:\underbrace{\begin{minipage}{48.% 0pt} \begin{picture}(48.0,36.0) \put(6.0,24.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(1.0,25.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(1.0,35.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(1.0,35.0){\line(0,-1){10.0}} \put(24.0,30.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0){$\scriptstyle f$}} \put(18.0,24.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(12.0,25.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(12.0,35.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(30.0,24.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(24.0,25.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(24.0,35.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(42.0,24.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(47.0,25.0){\line(-1,0){12.0}} \put(47.0,35.0){\line(-1,0){12.0}} \put(47.0,35.0){\line(0,-1){10.0}} \put(6.0,24.0){\line(0,-1){12.0}} \put(18.0,24.0){\line(0,-1){12.0}} \put(30.0,18.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0){$\scriptstyle\cdots$}} \put(42.0,24.0){\line(0,-1){12.0}} \put(6.0,0.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0)[b]{$V$}} \put(18.0,0.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0)[b]{$V$}} \put(30.0,0.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0)[b]{$\cdots$}} \put(42.0,0.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0)[b]{$V$}} \end{picture} {\vskip 10.75pt} \end{minipage}}_{n}\mapsto\begin{minipage}{72.0pt} \begin{picture}(72.0,60.0) \put(36.0,48.0){\oval(60.0,18.0)[t]} \put(6.0,48.0){\line(0,-1){12.0}} \put(18.0,36.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(13.0,37.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(13.0,47.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(13.0,47.0){\line(0,-1){10.0}} \put(36.0,42.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0){$\scriptstyle f$}} \put(30.0,36.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(24.0,37.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(24.0,47.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(42.0,36.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(36.0,37.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(36.0,47.0){\line(1,0){12.0}} \put(54.0,36.0){\line(0,1){1.0}} \put(59.0,37.0){\line(-1,0){12.0}} \put(59.0,47.0){\line(-1,0){12.0}} \put(59.0,47.0){\line(0,-1){10.0}} \put(66.0,48.0){\line(0,-1){12.0}} \put(12.0,36.0){\oval(12.0,18.0)[b]} \put(30.0,36.0){\line(0,-1){24.0}} \put(42.0,30.0){\makebox(0.0,0.0){$\s