Definition 11.1. We say that a nonempty total order $S$ is homogeneous if for any $P\in\operatorname{Pos}$ and $h,k\in\operatorname{Pos}(S,P)$ whenever $\operatorname{im}(h)=\operatorname{im}(k)$ then there are $e_{1},e_{2}\in\operatorname{Adj}(S)$ such that $(e_{1},\mathrm{id}_{P})\models h\preceq k$ and $(e_{2},\mathrm{id}_{P})\models k\preceq h$.
Definition 7.1. Suppose $S$ is a nonempty poset. A weak $S$-adjoint is a pair of $S$-continuous maps $h^{+}:Q\rightleftarrows P:h_{+}$ such that $\mathrm{id}_{Q}\preceq h_{+}h^{+}$ in $\operatorname{Pos}(\Lambda(S,Q),\Lambda(S,Q))$ and $h^{+}h_{+}\preceq\mathrm{id}_{P}$ in $\operatorname{Pos}(\Lambda(S,P),\Lambda(S,P))$, i.e., $k^{\prime}\preceq h_{+}h^{+}k^{\prime}$ for each $k^{\prime}\in\operatorname{Pos}(S,Q)$ and $h^{+}h_{+}k\preceq k$ for each $k\in\operatorname{Pos}(S,P)$. We write this as $h^{+}\,\sim\!\mid_{S}\,h_{+}$.
Definition 2.1. For $P,Q\in\operatorname{Pos}$ and $h,k\in\operatorname{Pos}(P,Q)$, we say that $k$ is taxotopic to $h$, written $k\preceq h$, if there are $f\in\operatorname{Adj}(P)$ and $g\in\operatorname{Adj}(Q)$ such that $k\circ f^{*}=g^{*}\circ h$ and $h\circ f_{*}=g_{*}\circ k$. We express this as $(f,g)\models k\preceq h$, read $f,g$ witness $k\preceq h$, if we want to emphasize the adjunctions.
Definition 11.6. A matching family $\{h_{Q}:S\to Q_{\bot}\mid Q\in\mathcal{Q}\}$ indexed by the elements of a cover $\mathcal{Q}$ of $P$ is said to have the amalgamation property if $\max\{h_{Q}(s)\mid Q\in\mathcal{Q}\}$ exists, denoted $p_{s}$, for each $s\in S$.
Definitions 8.4. The folding quotient: Given $Q\in\operatorname{Set}$ and a poset $(Q^{2},\leq)$ with coordinate symmetry, i.e., $(q_{1},q_{2})\leq(q^{\prime}_{1},q^{\prime}_{2})$ if and only if $(q_{2},q_{1})\leq(q^{\prime}_{2},q^{\prime}_{1})$, the folding quotient $\mbox{Fold}(Q^{2},\leq)$ is obtained by identifying the ordered pairs $(q_{1},q_{2})$ and $(q_{2},q_{1})$. The open book condition: Let $P$ be a non-empty connected poset. We say that the ordered pairs $(h_{1},h_{2}),(k_{1},k_{2})\in\Lambda(P)\times\Lambda(P)$ are linked by an open book condition if there exist $f,g,e\in\operatorname{Adj}(P)$ such that $(f,e)\models h_{1}\preceq k_{1}$ and $(g,e)\models h_{2}\preceq k_{2}$. We write this as $(h_{1},h_{2})\preceq^{o}(k_{1},k_{2})$. Note that $\preceq^{o}$ satisfies coordinate symmetry.
Definitions 12.1. For a finite connected poset $P$, the notations $\max P$ and $\min P$ denote the subsets of $P$ containing all maximal and minimal elements respectively. Define $T(P):=\bigcap_{x\in\max P}x^{\downarrow},\quad B(P):=\bigcap_{y\in\min P}y^{% \uparrow}.$ Set $T_{0}(P)=B_{0}(P):=P$ and, for each $n\geq 1$, define $T_{n+1}(P):=T(T_{n}(P))$ and $B_{n+1}(P):=B(B_{n}(P))$. Since $P$ is finite, the sequences $(T_{n}(P))_{n\geq 0}$ and $(B_{n}(P))_{n\geq 0}$ must stabilize. Define $t(P):=\min\{n\mid T_{n}(P)=T_{n+1}(P)\mbox{ or }T_{n+1}(P)=\emptyset\}$ and $b(P):=\min\{n\mid B_{n}(P)=B_{n+1}(P)\mbox{ or }B_{n+1}(P)=\emptyset\}$.
Definition 7.4. Let $P$ be a non-empty poset. Given $a<b$ in $P$, the closed interval $[a,b]$ is said to be a tunnel if the open interval $(a,b)$ contains at least two elements and for each $c\in(a,b)$ and $d\notin[a,b]$, if $c<d$ then $b<d$ and if $c>d$ then $a>d$.
Definition 11.5. Let $S$ be a homogeneous total order. A family $\{h_{Q}:S\to Q_{\bot}\mid Q\in\mathcal{Q}\}$ of monotone maps indexed by the elements of a cover $\mathcal{Q}$ of $P$ is a matching family if for each $s\in S$ and $Q^{\prime}\subseteq Q$ in $\mathcal{Q}$, if $h_{Q}(s^{\downarrow})\cap Q^{\prime}$ is nonempty then its maximum exists and $h_{Q^{\prime}}(s)$ equals this maximum; otherwise $h_{Q^{\prime}}(s)=\bot$.
Definition 6.2. A monotone map $h:Q\to P$ is said have the extension property if each $f\in\operatorname{Adj}(Q)$ yields an adjunction $f^{ext}$ on $P$ such that $(f,f^{ext})\models h\preceq h$. We denote by $\mathcal{E}$ the subcategory of $\operatorname{Pos}$ consisting of monotone maps with extension property.
Definition 10.2. We say that a cover $\mathcal{Q}$ of a poset $P$ is chain-compact if for every maximal chain $I$ in $P$ (existence by Zorn’s lemma) there exists a finite subset $\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}$ of $\mathcal{Q}$ such that • $I\subseteq\bigcup\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}$, • for each $a<b$ in $Q\cap I$, $[a,b]\cap I\subseteq Q$, • for each $a<b$ in $I$, if there does not exist any $Q\in\mathcal{Q}$ with $a,b\in Q$, then there is a finite subchain $a=p_{0}<p_{1}<\ldots<p_{l}=b$ of $I$ such that for each $1\leq i\leq l$, there is some $Q\in\mathcal{Q}^{\prime}$ such that $[p_{i-1},p_{i}]\cap I\subseteq Q$.
Definition 1.2. The local category of adjunctions on $\mathcal{C}$, denoted $\operatorname{Loc}_{\operatorname{adj}}(\mathcal{C})$, has as objects the objects of $\mathcal{C}$ and as morphisms $C\to D$ those adjunctions $F\in\operatorname{Adj}(\mathcal{C})$ which satisfy $F^{*}D=C$ and $F_{*}C=D$. We will use the notation $F\models C\preceq D$ to denote $F\in\operatorname{Loc}_{\operatorname{adj}}(\mathcal{C})(C,D)$.
Definition 10.3. Let $\mathcal{Q}$ be a cover of $P$. A family of maps $(k_{Q}:Q\to Q)_{Q\in\mathcal{Q}}$ is said to be compatible if whenever $Q^{\prime}\subseteq Q$ in $\mathcal{Q}$ we have $k_{Q^{\prime}}(q^{\prime})=k_{Q}(q^{\prime})$ for each $q^{\prime}\in Q^{\prime}$. A family of adjunctions $(f_{Q}\in\operatorname{Adj}(Q))_{Q\in\mathcal{Q}}$ is said to be compatible if whenever $Q^{\prime}\subseteq Q$ in $\mathcal{Q}$ we have $(f_{Q})\mathord{\mid}_{Q^{\prime}}=f_{Q^{\prime}}$. A cover $\mathcal{Q}$ of $P$ is said to have the extension property if for every compatible family $\{f_{Q}\in\operatorname{Adj}(Q):Q\in\mathcal{Q}\}$ of adjunctions, there exists $f\in\operatorname{Adj}(P)$ with $f\mathord{\mid}_{Q}=f_{Q}$ for each $Q\in\mathcal{Q}$.
Definitions 6.4. An order embedding $i:Q\rightarrowtail P$ is said to have the restriction property if each $f\in\operatorname{Adj}(P)$ restricts to an adjunction $f\mathord{\mid}_{Q}$ on $Q$, i.e., $(f\mathord{\mid}_{Q},f)\models i\preceq i$. We denote by $\mathcal{R}$ the subcategory of $\operatorname{Pos}$ consisting of order embeddings with restriction property. We denote by $\operatorname{Sub}_{w}(P)$ (resp. $\operatorname{Sub}_{s}(P)$) the collection of all subsets $Q\subseteq P$ such that the inclusion $Q\rightarrowtail P$ is in $\mathcal{R}$ (resp. in $\mathcal{R}\cap\mathcal{E}$).
Definition 3.1. The fundamental poset of the pair $\langle P,Q\rangle$, denoted $\Lambda(P,Q)$, is defined to be the posetal reflection of the taxotopy preorder $(\operatorname{Pos}(P,Q),\preceq)$.
Definition 5.1. Suppose $P\in\operatorname{Pos}$. The cone over $P$ is a poset obtained from $P$ by adjoining a top and a bottom element. More precisely, we choose two elements $\top,\bot\notin P$. The cone $CP$ has $P\cup\{\top,\bot\}$ as the underlying set, admits an order embedding $P\rightarrowtail CP$, and has relations $\bot<p<\top$ for each $p\in P$.
